<h1 class="rm-manual">Two million New Yorkers may not have access to food after coronavirus pandemic: de Blasio</h1>
<p class="rm-manual"> <span>By <a href="file:///anna-sanders-staff.html#nt=byline" rel="author"><span>Anna Sanders</span></a> </span> </p>
<p class="rm-manual"> <span>New York Daily News</span> <span>|</span> </p>
<p class="rm-manual"> <span> Apr 23, 2020 </span> <span>|</span> <span> 3:56 PM </span> </p>
<p> Long Island Relief Fund founder Patrick Thompson (l.) coordinates 
meals with the owner of Little Chef Little Cafe, Diana Manalang. The 
meals are funded by Long Island Relief Fund to ensure residents have 
food and support local businesses. At Little Chef Little Cafe in Long 
Island City, Queens on Wednesday April 15, 2020. <span>(Wes Parnell/NEW YORK DAILY NEWS)</span></p>
<p> As many as two million New Yorkers could lack access to enough food 
because of the economic fallout from coronavirus, Mayor de Blasio said 
Thursday.</p>
<p> About 1.2 million people were food insecure in the city even before 
the five boroughs were hit by the pandemic, which is expected to put an 
estimated half-million New Yorkers out of work.</p>
<p> “The number of people who are food insecure is unquestionably going 
up,” de Blasio said during a briefing. “I fear the number’s going to be 
around two million New Yorkers who are food insecure as this crisis 
deepens, and that’s a horrifying number.”</p>
<p> Last week de Blasio announced the city will <a href="https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-hunger-initiative-pandemic-new-york-city-20200415-n5mml5c4orhizhq37c5duawa3e-story.html">spend $170 million in the coming months to ensure no New Yorkers go hungry because of coronavirus</a>. The city expects to deliver 10 million free meals to residents in April and up to 15 million meals in May.</p>
<p class=""> Grab-and-go meals are available at <a href="https://www.schools.nyc.gov/school-life/food/free-meals">435 school sites as part of this effort</a>.</p>
